<tr><td bgcolor="#3F403F" width="98%" class="cheader"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="...328fedb22570524062aeb1303" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php3'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></td><td bgcolor="3F403F" valign="top" align="right" width="22"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/topcorner.gif" width="23" height="22" border="0" vspace="0" hspace="0" align="right"></td></tr>
<tr><td width="98%" colspan=2><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" class="cbody">
<tr><td><font class="h1font"> What does it take to prepare and run a Great Tournament (part1)<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/starwarsccg/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.95)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=7450'>Wojciech "Hipo" Wisniewski</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/starwarsccg/main/mpage.php?member=7450&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> July 7, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> A couple of years back, when SW was still one of the most popular CCG it was quite easy to organize and run a succesful tournament, and by succesful I mean one with quite a lot players and fair prizes. Unfortunately it&#39;s a little different now. So how to do it, how to prepare and run great tournament? I&#39;m facing this chalange right about now, since in about month and a half there will be Polish Nationals.<br />
Oh, I didn&#39;t mentioned that I&#39;m from Poland :) becouse of that people from States or Canada might no find this article as useful as people from Europe but I hope most of you will like it.<br />
<br />
PLACE<br />
So first I have to find a place where a tournament take place, the place shouldn&#39;t be far from train station so people how will come by trane won&#39;t have a hard time finding it. It can be a local card store if they have enough space and will let you do it, it&#39;s the best way I think, but if it&#39;s not possible, you may try local library or maybe even a pub (we had a tournament in a pub once, and since there wasn&#39;t any children or teenagers playing we had a really good time ;)<br />
You can also make the tournament at the convention, but I don&#39;t like this idea since people responsible to organizing the whole convention usualy are ignoring cardplayers and if someone want to play in the tournament he has to pay whole entry fee and prizes supported by the convention aren&#39;t even worth half the fee.<br />
Oh, I forgot that when you&#39;re deciding where to hold a tourney, you should first decide which city it will be in. There are I think two strategies of doing that, first is to hold a tournament in a city that has a biggest player base so we are sure we will have a decent number of players. But if you know that there are some people that will come to the tourney even to a different city, you can make it somewhere else to promote the game - we did something like that two weeks ago sice there are about 10 players from 3 different cities that are attending every tournament even if they have to travel quite far.<br />
As for our Nationals we&#39;ve choosen a city with a biggest player base (Krakow if that ells you anything) since it will be a big event and it would be hard to make it and promote it anywhere else. But our local store is to small to hold it, so we found ourselves a bigger place, place where annual small conventions are usualy held but this time, we will have it all to ourselves.<br />
<br />
PEOPLE <br />
But enough about the place, it&#39;s time worry about attendance, after all this should be the biggest tournament of the year.  You should start with local players, becouse it&#39;s sometimes the hardest task to make them come to the tournament. There is of course a loyal group of SWCCG players, you don&#39;t have to worry abut them, they&#39;ll be there for sure, but there ae still some people who have the cards but aren&#39;t playing as often as they should. So you must talk to every one of them, tell them that without them the tournament won&#39;t be the same (yeah, right;) ) and stuff like that, some of them will be lured byt great prizes, some of the by the possiblity of seeing old friends and so on. Of course not all of them will come, but even 50% will be good.<br />
As your next step you must talk to the people from outside the chosen city, mailing lists and SWCCG Homepages should be a good start, but asit may make many people aware of the tournament, if won&#39;t convince too many of them to come.  In my quite long career as SWCCG player I&#39;ve been to many tournaments and for all those years I&#39;ve met a lot of players, some of them are still playing and we&#39;re still friends, so each time I want to make a tournament I contact them personaly and usualy I&#39;m able to convice them to come. I&#39;m sure all CCG players who attended many tournament have many such friends and it&#39;s not that hard to make them come, especialy that it will be an oportunity to meet people who we haven&#39;t seen in a long time. So I encourage everybody who are thinking about organizing a tournaments to try to do it as big as it can and show eevrybody taht our &quot;dead&quot; game isn&#39;t dead at all.<br />
<br />
That&#39;s all for now, but stay tuned for part 2 of this article which will continue adventures of 5P theory in the world of SWCCG (well, it our case it will be 4P as PROMOTION and PRIZES will be talked about in part2). I just hope you weren&#39;t very bored :)<br />
Thanks<br />
Hipo<br />
